    "88190384": {
      "title": "Male genitalia of Lepidoptera: Morphology and nomenclature III. Appendages pertaining to the tenth somite",
      "abstract": "This paper deals with appendages of the tenth abdominal segment of the Heteroneura which form terminal processes situated at the top of the male genitalia and surround dorsally and ventrally the anal projection."
    },
    "87288831": {
      "title": "Male genitalia of Lepidoptera: norphology and nomenclature I. Divisions of the valvae in Rhopalocera, Phalaenidae (=Noctudae) and Geometridae",
      "abstract": "In a number of specialized groups of Lepidoptera the paired clasping organs, the valvae, of the male genital armature frequently show such complexity of structure that an appropriate subdivision of these organs is profitable for descriptive purposes. Attempts to divide the valvae into several parts have hitherto been made repeatedly, especially in the Rhopalocera[6][1], Phalaenidae (= Noctuidae) and Geometridae. Pierce's system (1909, 1914) devised originally for description of the male genitalia of the latter two familes, has since been accepted, at least in part, by some of the most prominent workers (Busck and Heinrich, 1921; Eyer, 1924; Mehta, 1933; Viette, 1948). For other families, especially those belonging to the Rhopalocera, other systems of terminology and of subdivision have been presented (Petersen, 1904; Warren, 1926). However, the morpological basis of the proposed systems is largely obscure, so that there might be a serious question whether it is possible to establish a generalized principle, useful in dividing the valvae of differently modified types into several regions, which above all must readily be applicable with reasonable homologies throughout the more specialized groups of Lepidoptera. ::: ::: [1]: #fn-3"
    }
  },
